Here's a layered approach to diagnose HttpClient timeouts in a .NET 8 Windows service:

**1. .NET-level diagnostics (start here)**
```csharp
// Enable HttpClient event tracing via environment variable
// In your service's environment:
DOTNET_SYSTEM_NET_HTTP_ENABLEACTIVITYPROPAGATION=true
```

Or add to your service startup:
```csharp
using var listener = new HttpEventListener();

sealed class HttpEventListener : EventListener
{
    protected override void OnEventSourceCreated(EventSource src)
    {
        if (src.Name is "System.Net.Http" or "System.Net.Sockets" or "System.Net.Security")
            EnableEvents(src, EventLevel.LogVerbose);
    }

    protected override void OnEventWritten(EventWrittenEventArgs e)
        => Console.WriteLine($"{e.TimeStamp:HH:mm:ss.fff} [{e.EventSource.Name}] {e.EventName}: " +
           string.Join(", ", e.PayloadNames?.Zip(e.Payload ?? [], (k, v) => $"{k}={v}") ?? []));
}
```

**2. Network-level capture (Wireshark/netsh)**
```powershell
# Start a packet capture scoped to your service's traffic
netsh trace start capture=yes tracefile=C:\diag\nettrace.etl maxsize=512
# ... reproduce the issue ...
netsh trace stop
```

**3. Common root causes to check**

| Cause | Diagnostic command |
|---|---|
| Port exhaustion | `netstat -ano | findstr TIME_WAIT \| Measure-Object` |
| DNS resolution delays | `Measure-Command { Resolve-DnsName api.example.com }` |
| Socket pool starvation | Check if you're creating `new HttpClient()` per request (don't) |
| Proxy/firewall rules | `netsh winhttp show proxy` |
| TLS handshake stalls | Visible in the EventListener above via `System.Net.Security` |

**4. Quick wins to validate**
```csharp
// Set an explicit shorter timeout to fail fast & confirm the hang:
httpClient.Timeout = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(10);

// Use IHttpClientFactory (avoids socket exhaustion):
services.AddHttpClient("ExternalApi", c =>
{
    c.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");
    c.Timeout = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30);
})
.ConfigurePrimaryHttpMessageHandler(() => new SocketsHttpHandler
{
    PooledConnectionLifetime = TimeSpan.FromMinutes(2),  // DNS rotation
    ConnectTimeout = TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5),             // fast-fail on connect
    EnableMultipleHttp2Connections = true,
});
```

**Recommended order:** Check `TIME_WAIT` count and DNS first (fastest), then add the `EventListener`, then packet-capture if still unclear. The most frequent cause in Windows services is **socket exhaustion** from not using `IHttpClientFactory`.
